comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text:
"RW Wade" is probably to be identifed with Robert Watson Wade, Esq., M.R.I.A. (ca. 1755-ca. 1836), economist, translator and bibliophile. He served as Accountant-General in the Bank of Ireland until 1783, when he was succeeded by Thomas Williams (cf. H. Smyth, "Some Notes on Charles Wye Williams, His Family, Their Life and Times," Dublin Historical Record 49.1 (1996), p. 65). He then took up the post of First Clerk of the Irish Treasury. In that same year
"... he commissioned a medal from William Mossop of Dublin, for presentation to Dr Henry Quin in appreciation of his successful treatment of Wade, and was resident in Ireland until at least 1790: The Dictionary of Irish Architects 1720-1940 records that 'Bryan Bolger measured stone and brickwork executed by E[dward] Smith for Robert Watson Wade at Knockmaroon, Co. Dublin, in 1787, 1789, and 1790' (s.n. Smith). Wade appears to have moved to England at the beginning of the nineteenth century, becoming Secretary to the Committee of the Stock Exchange, and his will, dated 18 April 1835, describes him as 'Gentleman of Saint Pancras, Middlesex'. In Ireland he had subscribed to a number of literary works published in Dublin, and in England he seems to have continued his participation in literary life, befriending (amongst others) Thomas Frognal Dibdin, to whose works he subscribed. "Dibdin paid tribute to his 'near neighbour' and 'affectionate friend', who gave 'constant and valuable aid' with the writing of Bibliomania, in Reminiscences of a Literary Life (London: 1836) ... In a footnote, Dibdin also ... expands on [Wade's] interest in Petrarch: 'His knowledge of the Italian language was, I have understood, minute and critical; and his attachment to Petrarch ardent and incessant. He was always at work upon the Sonnets; and yet scarcely ever satisfied with his translations, which were rhythmical. What he aimed at was, the strictest literal version. In consequence, the original, as is the case with Cowper's version of Homer, always appeared in a cold, drab-coloured, Quaker-dress; or it was the countenance of Petrarch without blood in his cheek or inspiration in his eye' (I, p. 330). Wade was also the author of two works on economics -- The Stock-Holder's Assistant (s.l.: 1806) and Tables Shewing the Amount of any Quantity of Omnium (London: 1810) -- and contributed to others."--Henry Sotheran Ltd., Spring Miscellany 2013: Including a Supplement of Books from the Library of Fleur Cowles (London: Sotheran, 2013), p. 41-42.
Dibdin writes of Wade in the past tense in Reminiscences and notes "he was turned of eighty when he died" (I, p. 331); he also quotes the poetic epistle which Wade wrote to him in the persona and language of William Caxton and published in the Gentleman's Magazine in 1811 (v. 81, pt. 2, p. 558). Wade was also a friend of Anglo-Irish antiquarian Joseph Cooper Walker, in the editor's preface to whose posthumously published (1815) Memoirs of Alessandro Tassoni he is identified as private secretary to the chancellor of the Irish Exchequer (p. xxxix). In 1814, in his capacity as secretary of the stock exchange, he was called as a witness in the trial of the conspirators involved in the Great Stock Exchange Fraud, though his testimony was brief and evidently uncontroversial. He was purchasing books as late as 1832, when he acquired and had bound an English-Irish ms. phrasebook (later part of the Phillipps collection as MS 17832). Established heading: Wade, Robert Watson

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: This was the court library of the Fürstpropstei Ellwangen (English article here). Originally founded as a Benedictine monastery in the eighth century and raised to the eminence of a Reichsabtei in the ninth, the original Stift Ellwangen had by the early 15th century declined to the point that the Benedictines abandoned it. In 1460 the foundation was given over to a college of secular (Augustinian) canons presided over by a Fürstpropst (prince-provost), who ruled not only the college itself but a small principality centered on the city of Ellwangen (near the eastern border of what is now Baden-Württemberg). The library was a later development, its volumes acquired during the 17th and 18th centuries as the prince-provost's private collection. The college was secularized in 1802; the library was dissolved in 1806, most of the books remaining in Ellwangen to form the basis of the collection of the short-lived Katholisch-Theologische Friedrichs-Universität Ellwangen (1812-1817), subsequently absorbed into the Universität Tübingen as its theological faculty (cf. H. Hummel, ed., Katalog der Inkunabeln in Bibliotheken der Diözese Rottenburg-Stuttgart (Wiesbaden: Harrassowitz, 1993), p. 290). DNB heading: Stift Ellwangen (This heading definitely covers the foundation's Augustinian period as well as its Benedictine one; the LC heading, Benediktinerkloster Ellwangen, is specific to the Benedictine foundation.)

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text:
Not necessarily a woman's achievement by shape; cf. this 1765 engraving by Carlo Domenico Melini of a portrait of Charles-Joseph de Pollinchove (1675-1756) by Joseph Aved with these arms in the tail margin using an oval. The metadata for the portrait identifies him as "duc de Pollinchove," which would jive with the coronet. R. du Sart de Bouland, in "Quelqes ex-libris tournaisiens," in Annales de Société historique et archéologique de Tournai, n.s., t. 9 (1905), describes a bookplate similar to the one depicted here and identifies the owner as Charles-Joseph de Pollinchove:
L'écu rond supporté par deux griffons surmonté de la couronne de marquis, le tout reposant sur un petit socle de style, et encadré dans un filet simple de 67 millim. de hauteur sur 49 de largeur. Gravure sur cuivre. (P. 459)
Our bookplate does appear to be engraved and measures 66 x 49 mm., but the crown looks ducal to me.

comment.text: Bookplate of E.P. (i.e. Edward Percy) Jacobsen (d. 1915), English historian and book collector. He was a friend of Wilfred Merton (1888-1957), who described him as an "ardent but impecunious booklover" in a note in Beinecke MS 342. In an advertisement for his 1892 translation of Charles Gide's Principles of Political Economy, he is described as being "formerly of University College, London". He appears to have been an examiner in English for the Civil Service under James Bonar (an economist who provided the introduction to the aforementioned translation of Gide's book) in 1899; cf. Reports from Commissioners, Inspectors and Others, v. 18 (1900), p. xiv. His death was reported in the 17 June 1915 issue of the British and Colonial Printer and Stationer, p. 13, which notes that he "was one of the earliest shareholders of the [Bookbinders Cooperative] Society, and succeeded Dr. J[ames] Bonar on the committee about nine years ago, when the latter gentleman went to Canada. Mr. Jacobsen was a good friend of the Society and of the workers individually, and they miss his kindly help and sympathy." Established form: Jacobsen, Edward Percy

Egloffstein is a municipality in Franconian Switzerland (Bavaria, Germany). The von Egloffsteins are a knightly family who held various properties in the region. H. Kunstmann notes ownership of a bower associated with Burg Egloffstein by a Hans Christoph, son of Veit Rochius von Egloffstein, Amtmann zu Leienfels, beginning in 1558. Cf. Sotheby, Wilkinson & Hodge, Catalogue of a selected portion of the renowned library at Wilton House, Salisbury, the property of the Right Hon. the Earl of Pembroke ... which will be sold by auction ... on Thursday, the 25th of June, 1914, and following day (London, 1914), no. 107. Charles Sessler (1854-1935) was born in Vienna, Austria, and emigrated to the United States in 1880. After a successful career as a Bible salesman in New York City, he moved to Philadelphia in 1882 and became a bookseller with premises at 1018 Chestnut Street. Subsequently he moved to 1530 Chestnut Street and then to 1310 Walnut Street (purportedly after an appointment with Henry E. Huntington went south when the roof began leaking on his distinguished customer). A notable Dickensian, in 1907 he founded the Philadelphia chapter of the Dickens Fellowship. On April 29, 1914, he (along with rival bookseller A.S.W. Rosenbach) acted in a benefit performance at the Academy of Music, a mock trial of John Jasper for the murder of Edwin Drood (Jasper was acquitted).

comment.text: Bookplate (with motto: Fortis in arduis) of James Wyllie Guild (1826-1894), Scottish public accountant and antiquarian. The son of a solicitor, he was born in Arbroath, Scotland, and educated at the Royal High School in Edinburgh. A founding member of the Institute of Accountants and Actuaries in Glasgow (IAAG), he served as its secretary (1867-1873), president (1873-1881), and treasurer (1881-1894). In 1851 he married Clarissa Finlay, with whom he had ten children. Over 3000 items from his library and antiquarian collections were sold at auction in April 1888; cf. Catalogue of the Valuable Library of J. Wyllie Guild ... (Edinburgh: Chapman, 1888). For his biography, see his entry in T.A. Lee, Seekers of Truth: The Scottish Founders of Modern Public Accountancy (Oxford: JAI Press, 2006). Established heading: Guild, James Wyllie

Peter Falck 1516 [Early ms. ownership inscription of humanist Peter Falck (ca. 1468-1519) and friends in red ink, struck through in brown ink, followed by early ms. inscription quoting a pious saying of St. Jerome in red ink in the same hand between drawings of a Jerusalem cross and an unidentified symbol. Beneath these in dark ink is Falck's dated 16th-century autograph, the name struck through, above a (later?) drawing of his coat of arms. Peter Falck was a Swiss humanist known to Erasmus (cf. his entry in Contemporaries of Erasmus) who made pilgrimages to Jerusalem in 1515 and 1519. According to this description of another of Falck's books with similar provenance, "After his death Falck's library passed to his daughter Ursula von Praroman. It was subsequently divided between her two sons Nikolaus and Wilhelm, and passed down through their families, to be more or less reunited in the late 17th century in the Capuchin convent at Fribourg. The present volume was one of those inherited by Wilhelm; this group passed by descent to one Anna Marie von Lanthen-Heidt, a wealthy noblewoman who had married Wilhelm's grandson Nikolaus von Praroman en secondes noces. After her husband's death in 1675 Anna gave the books to her friend the vicar-general Heinrich Fuchs.
